-- C3 AnnotationTooGeneral: an annotation must not claim more polymorphism than
-- the expression actually has.  `g : T -> T` (its match grounds the argument to
-- the concrete type `T`), so annotating it `(g : a -> a)` over-claims — the
-- annotation tyvar `a` is forced to `T` by unification.  Both the oracle and the
-- self-hosted typechecker reject this with the same AnnotationTooGeneral message.
-- (A genuinely-polymorphic value like `id x = x` annotated `(id : a -> a)` stays
-- accepted, since `a` remains a distinct unbound variable after unification.)
data T = MkT
g x = match x
  MkT => MkT
h = (g : a -> a)
